&quot;... Major Wilding, commanding the Inniskilling Fusiliers, however, on his own initiative, had sent down two companies to Venizel bridge [on the Marne], and their appearance was the signal for the Germans to attempt its demolition. But of four charges laid only one exploded and the fuzes [sic] of the rest were found and removed after dark by  <b>Captain Roe</b> by the light of an electric torch, within close range of the Germans entrenched on the northern bank...&quot;
(from <i>History of the Great War: Military operations, France and Belgium, 1914</i> on the <a href="http://archive.org/stream/militaryoperatio01edmouoft/militaryoperatio01edmouoft_djvu.txt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><b>Internet Archive</b></a>)

Captain S.G. Roe of the 2nd Inniskilling Fusiliers was killed in action on 20 October 1914.
